What you’re describing is actually a very recognizable human pattern, not something strange or “crazy.”

When you spend decades tightly coupled to someone—especially a twin—your brain doesn’t just like them, it builds them into its operating system.

⸻

What’s really happening

That kind of bond creates a shared loop:

* You predict each other
* You check decisions against each other
* You co-regulate (emotion, stress, confidence)

Over time, your brain effectively says:

“Part of my thinking lives over there.”

When that person isn’t present, the system doesn’t shut off—it re-routes internally.

So you get:

* more self-talk
* simulating their voice / perspective
* “filling in” what they’d say

That’s not dysfunction—that’s adaptation.

⸻

The important distinction

There’s a difference between:

Healthy internalization

* “I can think through what he’d say”
* feels like simulation / perspective-taking
* you know it’s coming from you

vs

Destabilizing isolation

* losing track of what’s internal vs external
* feeling like thoughts aren’t yours
* disconnection from shared reality

What you described sounds much closer to the first.

⸻

Why it can look like “crazy” from the outside

People who haven’t had that level of connection don’t recognize:

* how much cognition can be distributed across relationships
* how natural it is to re-internalize it when separated

So when someone is:

* talking to themselves more
* referencing internalized others
* processing deeply alone

…it can look strange, but it’s often just:

a system compensating for missing external nodes

⸻

The trauma piece you mentioned

You’re also right about this:

When a key connection is suddenly removed (loss, distance, rupture), the brain may:

* intensify internal simulation
* hold onto that person cognitively
* over-rely on self-looping

That’s not weakness—it’s the brain trying to preserve stability.

⸻

The useful takeaway for you

What you noticed is actually high awareness:

You can see when you’re “running the dual system internally”

That’s a strength—because it means you can choose:

* when to use it (strategy, reflection, grounding)
* when to reconnect externally (so it doesn’t become closed-loop)

⸻

A clean way to frame it

Connection built the system
Absence reroutes it
Awareness lets you steer it

⸻

One thing to keep it healthy

Even if you can simulate your brother well, make sure you still:

* talk things out with real people
* expose your thinking to feedback
* stay anchored in shared reality

Because:

Closed loops feel complete—but open loops stay accurate

⸻

What you described isn’t “losing it.”

It’s:
what a deeply connected mind does when one of its primary anchors isn’t there.